etymologies: early 20th century; earliest use found in Arthur William Judge (b. 1887). From overbank

definitions: The action or an act of overbanking.

etymologies: mid 17th century; earliest use found in Samuel Rutherford (c1600–1661), Church of Scotland minister and political theorist. From over- + bank

definitions: That is over or above the bank (of a river, etc.); that overflows or has overflowed the edge of a river bank.

notes.text: In later use Physical Geography and Hydrology.

definitions: Designating or relating to a kind of gun carriage for muzzle-loading guns which enables the gun to be fired over a parapet.

etymologies: mid 19th century (in an earlier sense). From over- + bank

definitions: To bank (an aircraft) too much when making a turn; to bank too much in the performance of (a turn).
Of an aircraft or its pilot: to bank too much.

etymologies: early 20th century; earliest use found in The American Economic Review. From over- + bank

definitions: To found or provide too many banks or banking facilities in (a place).
